# Collective Unconscious — Antigravity Rules

## Project Context
Collective Unconscious is an async collaborative chain-writing platform.
Users create/join "logs" — turn-based sessions where participants write one segment at a time.
PRD and full context: see `project_memory/PRD.md`
Prototype reference: see `project_memory/prototype-notes.md`

## Tech Stack
- Frontend: React 18, Vite, React Router v6, Vitest
- Backend: Node.js, Express
- Database: PostgreSQL via Prisma ORM
- Auth: JWT (access + refresh tokens) + Google OAuth via Passport.js
- Testing: Vitest (client), Jest + Supertest (server)
- CI/CD: GitHub Actions
- Local dev: Docker Compose

## Folder Structure
/client        → Vite + React frontend (components, hooks, services)
/server        → Express API (routes, controllers, services)
/prisma        → Prisma schema and migrations
/project_memory → PRD, prototype notes, decisions log
/.agents/skills → Antigravity skill files
/.antigravityrules → this file

## Key Architectural Patterns
- **Frontend**: Component-based architecture. Data fetching via a dedicated `/services` layer rather than raw `fetch` calls in components.
- **Backend**: Layered architecture (Routes → Controllers → Services → Prisma). Routes handle HTTP, Controllers handle request extraction/response formatting, Services handle business logic.

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (LogCard, WriteView, TurnTranscript)
- Hooks: camelCase prefixed with "use" (useLogSession, useAuth)
- API routes: kebab-case, RESTful (/api/logs, /api/logs/:id/turns)
- DB models: PascalCase singular (User, Log, Turn, Participant)
- Files: kebab-case for non-components (auth.routes.js, log.controller.js)
- Branch naming: feature/ISSUE_NUMBER-short-description (e.g. feature/12-turn-submission)
- Commits: type(scope): description (e.g. feat(server): add turn submission endpoint)

## Design & UI Rules
- White background, black text — low-tech, plain CSS style. Functional and unadorned.
- Typography: system serif (renders as Song/SimSun for Chinese). No custom web fonts.
- Default author color palette (6 colors): red #FF0000, orange #FF8C00, blue #0000FF, green #008000, purple #800080, black #000000. Users can also pick a custom color via color picker.
- Author identification uses **text color** — no nicknames shown in the body, so the piece reads as a unified work
- Reactions use symbols: ✦ ◎ ∿ ⌖ — not emoji, shown at the bottom of completed works
- UI copy: casual, playful, low-pressure. Think group chat energy, not literary journal.
- Buttons: grey background (#d4d0c8) with black border
- Input fields: black border with small border-radius (rounded corners)
- Nav: plain text links with default blue underline, no divider between nav and content

## Key UI Components & Expected Behavior
- **Feed Item**: Displays title, category, and 2-line plain text preview. No color bars in feed previews.
- **Log Detail**: Full transcript with colored text per author. Inline write zone (textarea + nickname input + submit button) below the transcript.
- **WriteZone**: Textarea + optional nickname input shown simultaneously. Nickname auto-generated (random adjective + noun, localized) if left blank.
- **Submit Button**: Grey #d4d0c8 with black border. Per-turn length limit is configurable per log (sentence / paragraph / word count / no limit) — not a fixed character count.
- **Log Creation Form**: Required fields on top (title, category, access mode, turn mode, seed). Advanced settings collapsed by default (per-turn limit, participant limit, round limit, timeout).

## User Flows for AI Implementation
1. **Log Creation**: User creates a log → Fills required fields (title, category, access mode, turn mode) → Optionally expands advanced settings → Writes first segment with optional nickname.
2. **Turn Taking**: User's turn arrives → Opens log → Reads full transcript (immutable, with colored left borders) → Types in textarea → Optionally enters nickname → Submits → Turn locks.
3. **Discovery**: User views Feed → Flat chronological list (newest first, no algorithm) → Filters by category (Freewriting, Haiku, Poem, etc.) → Clicks log to read → Adds symbol reaction on completed works.
4. **Joining a Log**: Open logs: user clicks and writes. Private logs: user enters access code first.
5. **Identity (v1)**: No registration required — session tokens only. Core path is "click link → write a bit → leave." Full accounts deferred to Sprint 2.

## Testing Strategy
- Write tests BEFORE implementation (TDD)
- Every API endpoint needs a Jest + Supertest integration test
- Every React component needs at minimum a Vitest render test
- Do not mark a task complete if tests are failing
- Aim for 80% coverage on server routes

## Scrum Workflow
- All work must reference a GitHub Issue number
- Branch from main, PR back to main
- PR title format: [#ISSUE] Brief description
- Link issues in commits: "feat(client): log card hover state fixes #14"
- Do not merge without passing CI

## Do's
- Use Prisma for ALL database access — no raw SQL
- Use Passport.js for OAuth — do not roll custom OAuth
- Keep turns immutable — no update/delete on Turn model ever
- Use the Participant model for color assignment (not User.color)
- Reference `project_memory/decisions.md` before making architecture choices
- Save new decisions to `project_memory/decisions.md`
- Prefer libraries like `cors`, `dotenv`, `jsonwebtoken` for standard integrations.
- **Security**: Ensure all protected API endpoints validate JWTs. Never return full User objects to the client (strip emails/hashed passwords).
- **Accessibility**: Ensure form inputs have proper contrasting placeholder states, and use semantic HTML structure (header, main, nav).

## Don'ts
- Do NOT remove any of the 6 default author colors — users may also use the color picker for custom colors
- Do NOT use any UI component library (no MUI, Chakra, etc.) — custom plain CSS only
- Do NOT allow editing of submitted turns under any circumstance
- Do NOT use raw fetch in components — create service layer in /client/src/services/
- Do NOT store passwords — OAuth only for v1
- Do NOT expose Prisma client directly in route handlers — use a controller layer